t of its possessions\nin the West Indies\u2019\u2019 was introduced to\nday by Senator Reed, Democrat.\nLondon, Feby. 18th. \u2014While hunting\non Pnursday at Aldershot Prince Henvy\nwas thrown from his horse. a0\nConstantincple, Feby. 18th.\u2014Tiflis,\ncapital of the Republic of Georgia is\nthreatened by a Russio Armenian Soviet\nArav \"ne Georgian Govt. bas fled.\nLondon, Feb. 17th. \u2014The Prime Min\nisier speaking in th2 House of Commeons\ntonight made an earnest appeal to the\nbanks to take a fair share of the risks of\ngranting credit to the impoverished Eu\nropean countries and in this way aid\nthe development of trade. He argued\nthat trade was equally bad in all coun\ntries hence one must suppose that the\ngovernments were equally bad in every\ncouan ry and that trade would never re\nvive until all countries were rvuled by\nan anti-waste league. '\u2018We have never\n5 1. LhEu L X A NS\nhad a grear period of unemployment\nwith iess distress\u2019\u2019, said Mr. Llyod\nGeorge, \u2018\u2018because heretofore there has\nbeen no state provision of any kind,\nwhile today twelve millions of- people are\ninsured for eighteen shillings weekly\nagainst unemployment. Moreover by\nhuge eftforts the country has spent forty\nmillions in providing for unemployed\nfermer service men. Reviewing the\nGovernment\u2019s measures, the Premier\ncontinued. \u201c\u2018You will never solve the\nproblem until the workers come in a\nfriendly way to consider what is bes:\nin the interests of industry. This coun\ntry depends more on exports than any\nother country in the world. If inter\nnational t -ade fails I don\u2019t eare what you\ndo by legislation or administration you\nwill have nothing but starvation and\nruin\u2019\u2019. The Prime Minister declared\nthat the workers must be prepared\nto share with less fortunate mmen. He\nspoke very stiongly in reproaching the\nbuilding trade for hampering the en\ntrance of former service men. The\nstagnation of thke purchasing po..er of\nCentral Kurope, he said, was in conse\nquence of the wagr. The whole diffi\nculty was the estabiishment of credit.\nKverybody wanted the Govi. to gssume\nthe whole risk, but that was unfair,\nbecause it was a risk of the taxpayers.\nThe Govt. had failed to induce the banks\nto take any share in these abnormal risks,\nand now he appealed (0o \u2018he banks to do\nso. It was in tne interests of the coun\ntry\u2019s trad2 and that was as much to the\ninterest of the banks as toany other class.\nThey were the only people who could\nreally help and if they did so he believ\ned that it would be possible to make a\nstart. The Prime Minister emphasized the\nbaffling nature of the Austrian problem\nowing to the breaking up of the indus\ntrial and commerciai machinery through\nout the continent. He also ailuded to\nthe immmoderate outbursts of natioonalists\nin all countries,, saying, '\u2018we have it\nhere, in France and the United States, a\nsort of feeling that you must build a wall\naround you and never hand a cup to\nyour neighbour. People forg:t that coun\ntries are interdependent\u2019\u2019. \u2018\u2018Love your\nneighbour\u2019\u2019 is not only sound *\u2019hristiani\nty, but good business\u2019\u2019 This was greet\ned with Labourite eheers and shouts of\n\u201c\u2018come over here\u2019,. Mr. Lloyd George\nconcluded with the statement, \u2018'Central\nEurope will be paralyzed unless it begins\nto feel a little more neighbourly and it is\nthe couniry\u2019s business to lead the way\nagain in this international task\u2019\u2019.\nLondon, Feb. 17ci. \u2014Great Britain\nmust duricg the course of the next\nFinancial Year makeprovision to pay the\ninterest cr. the United States debt. This\nannouncement was made by Mr. Austen\nChamberlain to a trade deputation repre\nsenting th~ federation of the British\nindustries. The conference with the\nCha..cellor took place in the House of\nCommons, it was urged that owing to\nthe burden of Trade and the existing\nslump an effort should be made tv reduce\n#axation. Sir William Rylands, Presi\ndent of the Federation, painted. the\nbusiness outlook as exceedingly bad\nand becoming worse. He declared the\ncontinental pric s were absolutely defy.\ning DBritish compet tion in all markets,\nespecially in the iron and steel industries.\nMoreover, under the collapsed exchange\nbusiness was breaking down complete\nly. Sir William also asserted that\nsome of the European countries we%e\ndeliberately pursuing a policy of m\nflation because 1t gave them a com\nmercial advantage. He suggested\npostpone the debt redemption until\nthe nation was better able to afford it\nand so give the country the benefit of\nreduced taxation Mr. Chamberlain in\nthe course of a long reply, pointed out\nthat none of the matter referred to was\nunder the direet control of the Govt.\nHe explained the impossibility of reduc\ning the income tax, and expatiated on\ndoing every hing possible to redeem the\nnational debt in order so far as it could be\ndone to lighten the burden of the com\nmunity. He concluded with the an\nnouncement that interest on the United\nStates debt must be yaid.\nSaint Blasien, Bacen, Feb. 17th.\u2014Bat\ntleships won the war and will win fu\nture wars, is the opinion of Admiral\nVon Tirpitz, at one time head of the\nGerman fleet and Minister of the Navy\nduring t: e critical period of the historie\nstruggle. He reaffirmed his faith in sur\nface craft, during an interview here to\nday, and declared th t strangely enough\nowing to the peculiariaties of the war\nthe submarine had been given greater\nimportance than was warranted by the\nfacts. In reality the war so far as the\nsea was concerned, he said, was won by\nthe British High Seas Fie-t, and i(he\nverdict could have been reversed only\nthrough battleships.\nLondon, Feby. 18th. ''Negotiations\nwith the Egyptian Govi. for the conclu\nsion of a treaty according self govern\nment to Egypt are strongly advised in\nthe long awaited report by iLord Milner,\nformer Colonial Secretary, on the Egyp.\ntian question, presented to Parliament\ntoday The negotiations should be en\ntered upon without undue delay, Il.ord\nMilper declared. The seli-govt arant,\naccording to the recommendations of the\nreport, would be accompanied by the\nnecessary reservations upholding e\nessential British interests and uvrotect\ning che rights of foreign residents 'The\nreport exprezsses that it would be a great\nmisfortune it the present opoportunities\nwere lost.\nGrenada. Feb. 21st.\u2014The drug store\nof A. J. Frederick and Sons with rhree\nother adjoining houses in the business\nsection of the town weve totaily des\ntroyed by fire this morning. Damage\nestimated at about three thousand\npounds.","height":"17923","width":"15093"}}
